Pass-Fail
We would like to suggest that the faculty, administration, and students of Grinnell College do something
original and work toward establishment of a wide«
ranging pass~fail trading system.
The system is self explanation; a student would be
given one of two grades — pass or fail. This would be
the penultimate in trading plans and would supplies
the many varieties of number and letter systems. The
final step, of course, would be no grades, but it seems
that you just don’t get your $2,600 worth if you don’t
get a card with some grade rotation on it.
Carleton has recently extended a pass-fail system
to “courses for which the conventional trading system
might be deemed inappropriate.” This would include
courses like creative writing, studio art, and advanced
seminars.
Earlier, Carleton had given (and still gives) its
students the option of taking one course per semester
on the pass-fail plan. This system is designed to allow
students to take courses outside their motors without
fear of hunting their grade-point operates.
When Carleton institutes the pass-fail system,
concerned people there saw growing out of the normal
letter trading system, a “social infringement which
. resulted from the excessive competition for grades
in course work," One faculty member felt that the
new system was potentially of special benefit to “a
small, somewhat geographically isolated, residential
college like Carleton (which can‘t be more isolated
than Grinnell) in reviewing that “social estrangementr”
While it may be argued that Grinnell needs’t follow Carleton in every step it takes, it is not pleasant
that a school which purposes to be a leading liberal
arts college in the country generally wants for other
schools to do the experimenting in matters of higher
import than liberal arts examinations for seniors.
Carleton is not the only school experimenting
with pass-fail, Washington University in St. Louis is
studying the possibilities of such a plan San Jose State
in California offers its freshmen a modified rio-grade
tutorial system. The California Institute of Technology
has established a pass-fail system for freshmen to ease
freshman transition into college life.
We would like to suggest that the established system of grade-giving is provide a big playback in every
area except, perhaps, in a student’s major. Retention of
the standard trading system for studentsY areas of coilcentration should satisfy those who argue that the new
system might engineer admission into graduate school,
since a student’s major grades are presumably the most
important part of his transcript.
It has been mentioned, too, that a pass-fail system
might lesson motivation, Unfortunately, the present
system stresses motivation for grade-training rather
than for learning a subject well because it is a subject
the students want to learn,
As a Carleton professor noted, with the establishment of a pass-fail trading system, “the pressure to
obtain the reward of a better grade might well be replaced by the challenge of an opportunity to master or
to sample as much of the knowable as one is able, while
pricing, as a genuine community of scholars, more
.deeply and more widely into unknown areas. This
would be a requesting environment in which to live,"
The drawbacks of the present system become more
apparent as mounting instruments throughout the corn»
try cause increased competition that may not be ap—
parent to administrators in their booty positions or to
l the students who have no choice but ’to accept the competition cr lose the status that their hard-fought-for
700 plus board scores gave them.
Our proposal, then, would be for Grinnell to set up
a pass-fail trading system for all subjects except those
in a student's major. We understand that informal di
session among faculty members on the matter of trading systems is potential; we would urge formal dis—
emissions by faculty, administration, and students.
It is time to work out a realistic means of image-
;meeting a pass-fail trading system, and there is no
reason why Grinnell shouldn’t. be a leader in this area.
